        <h3>Contractor Foreman — Best for maximum features at minimum cost</h3>
        <p>If budget is the primary constraint, Contractor Foreman starts at $49/month and includes an impressive breadth of features — estimates, time tracking, invoices, scheduling, project management, equipment tracking, and more. It's not as polished as the others, but it covers more ground for less money.</p>

        <h3>Buildertrend — When you've grown out of the others</h3>
        <p>Buildertrend at $499/month is genuinely worth it for residential contractors who've scaled past $2M in revenue and are managing significant complexity. But for small contractors just getting started with software, it's expensive and more than you need right now.</p>

        <div class="cta-box">
          <p><strong>Growing fast? Buildertrend is the platform to graduate to as your business scales.</strong></p>
          <a href="https://www.buildertrend.com" rel="nofollow sponsored" class="btn btn-outline">Explore Buildertrend</a>
        </div>

        <h2>What to avoid as a small contractor</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Enterprise platforms before you need them:</strong> Procore, Sage, and Foundation are excellent — for large companies. Starting there as a 5-person shop will cost you time and money you don't have.</li>
          <li><strong>Platforms that require a consultant to set up:</strong> You should be able to go from signup to first estimate in a day, not a month.</li>
          <li><strong>Per-user pricing if your team fluctuates:</strong> Seasonal crews, occasional subs — flat-rate pricing is more predictable.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>The free option: is it worth it?</h2>
        <p>Several platforms offer free tiers (Fieldwire for 5 users, HubSpot's free CRM). For early-stage contractors, these can work temporarily. But free construction software typically lacks the invoicing, payment collection, and job costing features that make software actually save you money. Budgeting $100/month for proper software is one of the best investments a small contractor can make.</p>

        <h2>Start simple, scale up</h2>
        <p>The best approach for small contractors: start with Houzz Pro or JobTread. Use it consistently for 6–12 months. If you're tracking job costs, winning more bids, and getting paid faster — the software is working. If you outgrow it as you scale, graduating to Buildertrend is a straightforward migration.</p>

